abstract: In “Once Upon a Prime,” Sarah Hart explores the surprisingly deep relationship between mathematics and literature.

lead_paragraph: C.P. abstract: We look at Italy, the largest country in western Europe to elect a far-right government in decades.
snippet: We look at Italy, the largest country in western Europe to elect a far-right government in decades.
lead_paragraph: Italy, the world’s eighth-largest economy, elected a far-right government last week, with Giorgia Meloni as the likely next prime minister. It’s part of a trend: Her victory came shortly after Swedish elections that led to a far-right party becoming the second-largest in Parliament there.

abstract: By seizing the basketball star, the Russian president made things so painful for the U.S. that it capitulated and turned over a convicted arms dealer. Can the same tactic work in the war in Ukraine?
snippet: By seizing the basketball star, the Russian president made things so painful for the U.S. that it capitulated and turned over a convicted arms dealer. Can the same tactic work in the war in Ukraine?
lead_paragraph: President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia wants to prosecute his war in Ukraine in the same way he secured the freedom on Thursday of a major Russian arms dealer: inflict so much pain on Western governments that, eventually, they make a deal.

main: News Analysis: In Brittney Griner Deal, Putin Used Pain, a Familiar Lever

abstract: Three New York Times Magazine photo editors share their tips for creative captures.
snippet: Three New York Times Magazine photo editors share their tips for creative captures.
lead_paragraph: Outside a cabin in Los Angeles last spring, Amy Kellner, a senior photo editor for The New York Times Magazine, faced a conundrum. The prop stylist had ordered more than 100 wildflowers as well as proteas, tulips and artificial flowers so that the comedian Seth Rogen, the subject of a cover shoot, could lie down in them. But when the photographer, Chris Buck, took test shots from above, he realized that Mr. Rogen’s facial features would appear distorted from that angle. So Mr. Buck came up with a quick solution: String the blooms on chicken wire, held up by clamp stands — and ask a standing Rogen to stick his head through. “He was game,” Ms. Kellner said.

abstract: Yoav Gallant, who oversees Israel’s military, is the first minister in Benjamin Netanyahu’s government to criticize a plan to weaken the judiciary. His comments follow fears that weeks of unrest have undermined military capacity.

main: Israel’s Defense Minister Says Government Should Halt Contentious Judicial Plan

abstract: Young people are increasingly at ease consuming culture via digital avatars or made with artificial intelligence. Should the same moral guidelines and laws apply to those works?
snippet: Young people are increasingly at ease consuming culture via digital avatars or made with artificial intelligence. Should the same moral guidelines and laws apply to those works?
lead_paragraph: The story of FN Meka — a fictitious character billed as the first musical artist partly powered by artificial intelligence to be signed by a major record label — might seem like a bizarre one-off. In August, Capitol Records dropped FN Meka, whose look, outlaw persona and suggestive lyrics were inspired by real-life music stars like Travis Scott, 6ix9ine and Lil Pump, amid criticism that the project trafficked in stereotypes.

main: A ‘Virtual Rapper’ Was Fired. Questions About Art and Tech Remain.
print_headline: A ‘Virtual Rapper’ Is Fired. Questions Flourish.

abstract: It exposes the moral compromises of the left and the cultural impotence of the right.
snippet: It exposes the moral compromises of the left and the cultural impotence of the right.
lead_paragraph: The news that Kenneth Griffin, a hedge fund billionaire, is donating a cool $300 million to Harvard University, where his name will adorn the entire Graduate School of Arts and Sciences, provoked the kind of pan-ideological revulsion that in our polarized times only the richest Ivy League schools still reliably inspire.

main: Why the Left and the Right Hate Kenneth Griffin’s Huge Gift to Harvard
